  "title": "Semi-Supervised Learning for Molecular Graphs via Ensemble Consensus",
  "experiments_summary": "The paper evaluates an ensemble-based semi-supervised learning method across multiple molecular and graph datasets. For QM9, a 4-member PaiNN ensemble predicts 12 quantum chemical properties using 10% labeled and 90% unlabeled data, with hyperparameters (learning rate, weight decay) tuned per target and coupling weight γ searched over {1.0, 0.1, 0.01, 0.001, 0.0001}. The method is compared against supervised baselines, mean-teacher (decay rates {0.9, 0.95, 0.99, 0.995, 0.999}), and PSEUDOσ (1000 epochs initial training + 15 episodes of 100 epochs). For broader validation, GCN, GIN, and GatedGCN architectures (M=4) are tested on GNN+ benchmarks (ZINC, Peptides-struct, Peptides-func, ogbg-molhiv, ogbg-molpcba) with SSL parameters tuned on ZINC. Ensemble size scaling (M=2,3,4,8,16,32) is studied on QM9's U0 target and CIFAR-10 using ResNet-18 (5,000 labeled, 40,000 unlabeled samples). The training objective combines supervised loss (MSE for regression, cross-entropy for classification) with an ensemble consistency loss weighted by γ, where each model minimizes distance to the ensemble mean prediction (gradient detached). Calibration metrics (NLL, ECE, MCE, Brier score, AUC-ROC) are evaluated on CIFAR-10 and ogbg-molhiv. Ablation studies examine hard vs. soft labels, pairwise vs. mean ensemble loss, coupling weight robustness, scheduling strategies (constant/increase/bell), different loss functions (L1, L2, L∞, KL-divergence), and overfitting on unlabeled data. All results report mean ± 1.96 standard error across 5 seeds with 80/10/10 train/validation/test splits."
